passages.text: F1Q26 Review: Executing oPlan With Greater Visibility Through the Pipeline Supporting Likelihood of Upsides to Come; Reiterate

NetApp delivered to its own forecasts relative to both revenue and margins in F1Q, but given typical management conservatism early in the year, the company reiterated its full- year guidance. While within the earnings results investors might be concerned about the modest gross margin miss to consensus expectations, the product- mix led deviation from the midpoint of the guide is only modest (71.1% vs. guidance of 71%- 72% and consensus of 71.5%), and additionally not material enough to lead the management team to change its expectations for the full year (FY26); although the reiterated gross margin guide for the full year is likely helped by better outlook for Public Cloud gross margins where the company is raising its long- term gross margin expectations from 75%- 80% prior to 80%- 85%. On the flip- side, missed by investors within an earnings print that otherwise looked in- line at the surface was management's acknowledgment that the performance in the quarter in relation to revenue was better than expected by the company for F1Q, including revenues tracking modestly higher than midpoint of the guide for the quarter ( \(1.56 bn vs. guidance of\) 1.53 bn). Additionally, management highlighted higher confidence in its 2H FY26 guide relative to 90 days ago, hinting at higher visibility through its pipeline, leading us to expect potential raises to the full- year revenue guide in the coming quarters if performance continues to track above company guidance. The primary investor concern relative to FY26 remains relative to the implied acceleration from low- single digit growth y/y in revenues in F1H26 to mid- single digit growth in F2H26, but we believe 2H expectations are still broadly in line with typical seasonality with potential for upside from conversion of large datacenter modernization projects that the company is engaged with multiple customers on; additionally, the implied acceleration in y/y growth in 2HFY26 relative to 1HFY26 is largely explained by easier comps as well as lower headwinds on a y/y basis from Spot divestiture in 2H Y26. Moving away from the financials, following earnings reports from Storage companies today, we believe the demand backdrop for Storage remains resilient with potential easing of cautious spending from Enterprise customers evidenced in the first half of the calendar year, except for demand within the Public Sector, which remains challenged. We expect the growth outlook for NetApp to remain healthy in FY26 and the company is positioned to deliver upsides through the datacenter modernization projects prioritized by Enterprises as well as AI- related projects with Enterprise customers which are just starting to ramp. Reiterate Overweight on the combination of potential revenue upsides as well as robust margins that are underappreciated in the inexpensive valuation multiple (NTAP shares are trading at 13x NTM P/E vs. long- term historical multiple of 14x).

We rate shares of NetApp Overweight led by our expectations of resilient revenue growth helped by improving IT budgets toward datacenters and Storage infrastructure in preparation of Enterprises looking to leverage AI use cases, as well as continued share gains from the recent pace of innovation from NetApp relative to its product portfolio. In addition to recent expansion in the product portfolio via the addition of C- series products, we expect more launches in relation to C- series products, Block storage (ASA products), as well as products based on disaggregated architecture, which will further enhance the already robust product portfolio and drive growth.

Our December 2026 price target of \(\) 130\(is based on valuing our CY27E EPS at 14x target P/E multiple, which is largely in - line with the current multiple and is justified on account of better structural margins relative to companies with exposure to traditional IT Hardware demand.

bn, increasing \(+1\%\) y/y, driven by robust performance in Americas Commercial \((+12\%)\) y/y) offset to a large extent by US Public Sector \((- 26\%)\) y/y) and EMEA \((- 2\%)\) y/y). Although Public Cloud tracked to only \(y / y\) growth on an ex-Spot basis the growth was closer to \(+18\%\) y/y. Meanwhile, margins tracked to \(71.1\%\) (vs. JPMc of \(71.7\%\) and consensus of \(71.5\%\) , and guide of \(71\% - 72\%\) ), which in combination with seasonally higher opex resulted in operating margins tracking to \(25.7\%\) (vs. JPMc and consensus of \(25.6\%\) , and guide of \(- 25.5\%\) ), and translated to EPS of \(\) 1.55\(vs. JPMc of\) \ \(1.54\) , consensus of \(\) 1.53\(, and guide of\) \ \(1.48 - \S 1.58\) -

- F2Q26 (Oct-end) Guidance: Earnings track modestly ahead of consensus, despite in-line revenue and margins, mostly driven by below-the-line items. NetApp is guiding revenue to \(\) 1.615-\$1.765 bn (midpoint of \(\) 1.690\(bn) vs. JPMc of\) \ \(1.70\) bn, consensus of \(\) 1.68\(bn, implying a revenue growth of \(+2\%\) y/y, which on an ex-Spot basis would imply \(+3\%\) y/y growth. Gross margins are guided to \(70.5\% - 71.5\%\) vs. JPMc of \(71.2\%\) and consensus of \(71.3\%\) , and includes improvement in margins for Products along with further expansion in Public Cloud margins, which is now targeted to be \(80 - 85\%\) margin business (vs. prior target of \(75 - 80\%\) ). Operating margins are guided to \(28 - 29\%\) vs. JPMc of \(29.1\%\) and consensus of \(28.5\%\) , translating to an EPS guide of \(\) 1.84-\$1.94 vs. JPMc of \(\) 1.92\(and consensus of\) \ \(1.87\) -

- FY26 (Apr-end) Guidance: Reiterated prior guide for revenues, margins and earnings. NetApp is reiterating its FY26 revenue guide of \(\) 6.625\(bn -\) \ \(6.875\) bn, vs. JPMc and consensus of \(\) 6.8\(bn heading into the print. Additionally, gross margins guide is reiterated to\) 71\% - 72\% \(vs. JPMc and consensus of\) 71.5\% \(. Operating margins guide is reiterated to\) 28.8\% - 29.8\% \(, vs. JPMc of\) 29.4\% \(and consensus of\) 29.1\% \(heading into the print, driving EPS guidance of\) \ \(7.60 - \S 7.90\) , vs. JPMc of \(\) 7.85\(and consensus of\) \ \(7.75\) .
NetApp, Inc. (Overweight; Price Target: \(130.00)

We rate shares of NetApp Overweight led by our expectations of resilient revenue growth helped by improving IT budgets toward datacenters and Storage infrastructure in preparation of Enterprises looking to leverage AI use cases, as well as continued share gains from the recent pace of innovation from NetApp relative to its product portfolio. In addition to the recent expansion in the product portfolio via the addition of C- series products, we expect more launches in relation to C- series products, Block storage (ASA products), as well as products based on disaggregated architecture, which will further enhance the already robust product portfolio and drive growth.

Our December 2026 price target of \(130 is based on valuing our CY27E EPS at 14x target P/E multiple, which is largely in- line with the current multiple and is justified on account of better structural margins relative to companies with exposure to traditional IT Hardware demand.
